<div id="review_1295240347" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1295240347" />
    <a title="Colleen Halloran" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41332513-colleen-halloran"><img alt="Colleen Halloran" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1295240347?book_show_action=true">May 31, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Colleen Halloran" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Colleen Halloran" href="/user/show/41332513-colleen-halloran">Colleen Halloran</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1295240347" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2943765804974120315"> From the Notebooks of Melanin Sun was about betrayal. Melanin and his mother were extremely close until she came out of the closet. Melanin&apos;s thoughts and disapproval resembled how any child would have reacted to this situation. I enjoyed how by the end of the book he accepted her for who she is and he also accepted her partner. Even though Melanin was upset with his mother he still defended her when his friends were making fun of her. I think that that is the true meaning of family. I like how</span>
  <span id="freeText2943765804974120315" style="display:none"> From the Notebooks of Melanin Sun was about betrayal. Melanin and his mother were extremely close until she came out of the closet. Melanin's thoughts and disapproval resembled how any child would have reacted to this situation. I enjoyed how by the end of the book he accepted her for who she is and he also accepted her partner. Even though Melanin was upset with his mother he still defended her when his friends were making fun of her. I think that that is the true meaning of family. I like how Jacqueline Woodson showed how Melanin was feeling through his journals. I enjoyed how the story took apart the family for a period of time then brought it back together.<br /> I can connect to this story because there are some girls at Algonquin that are lesbian. One of which is a friend of mine. At first she was very shy about it because she was afraid she would be bullied for it. After awhile she became comfortable with herself and realized that it didn't matter what other people thought of her. Obviously she doesn't have a son that it really would matter too. Because Melanin's mother cares so much about him it was really hurting her inside. <br /> I recommend this book to teens or anyone older. This book teaches a lot about acceptance. And since all of us crave acceptance there will be a valuable lesson learned.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2943765804974120315" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


