<div id="review_1943092405" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1943092405" />
    <a title="Bogi Takács" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29924068-bogi-tak-cs"><img alt="Bogi Takács" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1452480596p2/29924068.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1943092405?book_show_action=true">Mar 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bogi Takács" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bogi Takács" href="/user/show/29924068-bogi-tak-cs">Bogi Takács</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1943092405" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16468781724354236641">If you read my reviews, you probably know that I&apos;m a Jacqueline Woodson fan, but this one didn&apos;t quite work for me.<br/><br/>This book is the kind of YA contemporary that frankly feels more like a historical now. It&apos;s about a young Black boy and his queer mother; and just so much has changed about queer rights since 1995, when it was published, that I simply can&apos;t see the entire plot go the way it goes.<br/><br/>Warning that this book has a LOT of outright hate speech and in general a huge amount of anti-queer sent</span>
  <span id="freeText16468781724354236641" style="display:none">If you read my reviews, you probably know that I'm a Jacqueline Woodson fan, but this one didn't quite work for me.<br /><br />This book is the kind of YA contemporary that frankly feels more like a historical now. It's about a young Black boy and his queer mother; and just so much has changed about queer rights since 1995, when it was published, that I simply can't see the entire plot go the way it goes.<br /><br />Warning that this book has a LOT of outright hate speech and in general a huge amount of anti-queer sentiment...<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[...mostly coming from the protagonist and point-of-view character. The entire book is basically him trying to not hate his mother so much for her being queer and in a relationship with a woman. Eventually he succeeds, but I frankly had hard time seeing what made him change his mind rather abruptly.<br /><br />Also the plotting didn't quite work for me - all the protagonist's reasons to hate queer people were only briefly referred to in retrospect and not actually shown before his feelings, only afterward. I get it that he's supposed to be afraid of being labeled gay by his classmates because he is sensitive and writes lyrical prose fragments, and has an interest in species extinction, but a lot of that hatred is not actually demonstrated before his reactions are introduced, so his extreme level of aversion does not come across as grounded. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
  <a data-text-id="16468781724354236641" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


